    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4c.28.9-11_0001a" />
                <note type="curatorial">104-2 Aly Collection</note>
                            
                
                <opener>
                <dateline>4-16-'60</dateline>
                
                
                <salute>Dear Lucile:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>I woke this morning remembering a sentence in my letter of the 14th to you. It is the one in which I attach "tremendous significance" to my growing feeling about animals. Certainly the language seems (and may be) most intemperate, but I really had something important in mind. I've been reading Stewart Edward White's "The Unobstructed Universe", and it started me thinking again about 
                    
                    <pb facs="nei.j4c.28.9-11_0001b"/>
                    <fw type="authorial">-2-</fw>
                    
                    a deeper phase of consequences than we poor self-conscious human beings <del/> know, except in deep sleep or in moments of illumination. <del/> (You will remember the line in <hi rend="underline">Jed Smith</hi> about "what trees appear to know" and "the still, enchanted way they grow". This is concerned with the same idea I had in mind when I wrote that sentence. We <hi rend="underline">do</hi> live largely in a shallow state of consciousness,
                    
                    <fw type="curatorial">9</fw>
                    <pb facs="nei.j4c.28.9-11_0002a"/>
                    <fw type="authorial">-3-</fw>
                    
                    don't we? And can we doubt that the world-view growing out of that habitual state is much more than a "highly organized <del/> misunderstanding" (Poetic Values, you'll remember). Well, when I'm feeling very close to a horse or a <del>dog <unclear/><unclear>something of</unclear></del>dog, it is as though I experienced something of the deep, <del><unclear>and</unclear></del> impersonal
                    
                    <pb facs="nei.j4c.28.9-11_0002b"/>
                    <fw type="authorial">-4-</fw>
                    
                    and untroubled consciousness that is utterly free of self-seeking in any form and is all out-giving and loving.</p>
                
                <p>Anyway, I've wanted to apologize (in the strict sense of the word) for a sentence that could <del/> seem merely silly.</p>
                
                <p>I'm not sure that I read Sinclair's book on the Sacco-Vanzetti affair, altho'<sic>although</sic> I knew all about it at the time. I'm glad Upton is still "looking out the window"</p>
                
                <closer>
                <salute>Affectionately</salute>
                <signed>John</signed>
                </closer>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">10</fw>
            </div1>
            
            
            
